{
  "doc_id": "26392",
  "text": "Inductive Power Transfer (IPT) is the most commonly used technique to wirelessly deliver power to particular electronic devices. This technique is based on magnetic coupling between a secondary remote coil and a primary coil that is driven by an alternating current. Both primary and secondary coils are usually implemented using Printed Spiral Coil (PSC) technology. Over the last several decades, many research works with respect to inductive powering have been published [CITATION_1] , [CITATION_2] . IPT has extensively been used for remote powering of implantable medical devices [CITATION_3] , [CITATION_4] . In addition, IPT applications are extended to many added value applications, such as self-powered wireless sensors, which are notably difficult to implement via hard-wired powering or battery replacement and maintenance. Moreover, inductive powering has gained significant interest for wireless battery charging applications of all types of mobile devices, such as digital cameras and laptop computers [CITATION_5] . Recently, inductive powering has also been extended to many electric vehicle applications [CITATION_6] .",
